Czech discovery: a substance that also works on 'stuffed' HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works with viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not work as strongly on common virus variants as one of the existing medicines.
The disease AIDS cannot be cured yet.
However, the combination of medications can prolong life and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of viral proliferation also results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which no medicinal products are effective anymore.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University of Prague) and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to how to deal with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances known as metalocarboranes act on the protein substance responsible for the proliferation of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block viral reproduction in a different way than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new 'improved' compounds prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-faceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms, coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Insidious and Persistent Virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus spread caused by HIV protease, no mature infection virus particles would be created.
When we eliminate HIV protease, we also eliminate the proliferation of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper published in the scientific journal Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed further.
A little weaker but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances on HIV protease has been tested in the test tube, including against their persistent (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of the metacarborane on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as on the clinically used medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the used medicinal products are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical formation, makes the Metalocarborans interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory for Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
