Free and voluntary vaccination against pneumococci
Infection against pneumococci changes the habit from January onwards.
It is said to be the first free and voluntary for families.
But already now there are voices that the compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
The preparations for the introduction of free vaccination against pneumococci culminate.
The medical institute already sets the maximum prices of the vaccines that the health insurance companies have to pay.
Experts are also aware of the vaccination procedure.
New vaccination
Vaccines free of charge for August children
Children can be vaccinated against pneumococci free of charge from January, which were born on 2 August last year and later.
The condition is that they have not yet received a vaccination dose.
Those who have started vaccination in the past year or earlier must also pay for further vaccination.
The first dose must be given between the 3rd and 5th months of the child's life.
Already last year, a quarter of the families had their children vaccinated against pneumococci.
The parents paid 1,600 crowns and more for one dose.
Four doses are required for the vaccination of the youngest children.
Overall, the experts estimate that the health insurance companies spend 300,000 to 450,000 kroner per year on the doses of the vaccine.
However, they save on the treatment that the children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 per year on all vaccinations of the children.
The mandatory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococci cause middle ear inflammation, but also severe infections including inflammation of the brain and blood poisoning.
Pneumococcal infections kill up to 28 children up to 10 years of age in hospitals.
Outside the Czech Republic, the compulsory vaccination of children against pneumococci was introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
As of January, this is to be paid by the insurance companies and voluntary.
For example, Rudolf Kalovsky, head of the Nahlas Citizens' Association, mentioned that the compulsory vaccination would be better.
His association already promotes long-term pneumococcal vaccination.
The experts at the international conference in which our association was involved were not very satisfied with the fact that we have voluntary vaccination.
That's not quite ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we have managed to achieve at least that.
I think that's the way we have to go now, Kalovsky pointed out.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococci.
At this moment we are not considering this at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sesen.
Voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages, the doctors claim.
Hana Cabrnochova, Chairman of the Society of Practical Pediatricians, admits that voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all children were vaccinated, one could think about reducing the number of re-inoculations "In a situation where the vaccine is so expensive, we understand the political decision that this vaccination was started as voluntary," says Cabrnochova, however.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of parents to vaccinate their infants against pneumococci from next year.
The vaccination against pneumococci is also groundbreaking in the fact that it is the first surface vaccination to be paid by health insurance and not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend the money on prevention, saving them for further treatment, says Cabrnochova.
Doctors have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However, this is a concern of the practical pediatricians involved in the purchase of vaccines.
According to the original plan, the vaccines should be bought by the insurance companies and the doctors should then receive them on the same route as other vaccines issued by the State to them.
Some MEPs feared, however, that the insurance companies would be able to "lead the money out of health insurance."
Therefore, doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves and wait until the insurance companies pay them.
According to the estimates, the individual doctors will have to invest 40,000 crowns per month, which is a significant sum.
This is not going to be easy, says Cabrnochova.
