Still her and us
Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters voted in favour of a construction ban on minarette and concerns about the alleged Islamization of Europe are widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, wrote a well-founded and well-considered report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of Europe's most declared secularised societies - and integrated.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Why the French don't love headscarves" (2006), an elegant and heavily arguing study of an issue that divided and occupied the country over a decade and a half, and whose effects can still be felt today.
Bowen's latest book offers a wider and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it, "Islamic freedom."
He is a good listener, he gives back debates between teachers and students about the questions they are most concerned about.
Should a Muslim marry (or both) in a mosque or town hall?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-based banking system to obtain a mortgage?
These seemingly profane matters, he claims, make up everyday life, in contrast to the political dramas that occupy the media.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of whom have a well-known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arab-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen in a modern secular society on the other.
They don't have all the arguments on their side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists that Bowen questioned are usually divided with their Salafi counterparts - advocates of purist Sunni Islam, which is connected with Saudi Arabia - which nowadays show a small but influential presence among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite, who are so passionately guarding the separation of church and state) really feel obliged to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who in turn had to make their historical compromise with secular republicanism.
He recognizes more of a "sharpening of the value screws" than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book one is inclined to say "Yes, but not yet."
