A Gradual Relaxation
Anchored in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial instrument introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Couples who violate this policy must expect enormous fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplaces.
Chinese state officials have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of natural land resources could be avoided, while human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of policies.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to abort.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude towards one-child policies.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many hard slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Beijing University's Institute of Population Research, said that government officials have even discussed more radical changes recently, such as allowing couples to have two children with an individual partner.
