UN Group designs emission reduction plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been marked by wild poses and mutual accusations -- once again focused on Friday with the publication of a document that will record an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialised nations having to shoulder the greatest burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, has highlighted both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that runs out of time, as more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent about the money supply that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrialised and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of the global temperature rise that policy makers would support.
The process is given great flexibility, according to John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, has compiled a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's leading climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, called "the big deal."
It shows the outline of a possible agreement whereby industrialised nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also given the talks on Friday a boost through its commitment to provide US$3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change - from mastering floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Friday still brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the conversations last week.
American climate commissioner Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialised countries, compared with voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if these are not financed by the industrialised nations.
This train announced that the Obama government is going on a harder line with China, not even two years ago, as a representative of the Bush administration.
The United States will not sign an agreement without larger emerging economies and taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text did not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern gave his statement one hour after the statement by Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei, who said that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked "reason" or that it was "highly irresponsible" of him that he said earlier this week that the United States would not help China financially to master global warming.
By putting the future economic direction of the great world powers at stake, breaking lines have emerged both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle relates equally to saving individual economies, as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States acting on their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the great powers are fighting to bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have gone over to more aggressive action to hold very high greenhouse gas emissions countries accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic domination will develop, says Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change indicated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will, at best, lead to a political agreement.
The alliance of small island states with 43 members presented a 24-page draft treaty early on Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive of the small island states exerts "political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks were given a new urgency when the delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues had to be resolved before the government leaders arrived in order to reach an agreement.
High-ranking representatives, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, got off their planes and rushed through the corridors of the Bella Center to meet behind closed doors and press conferences to pinpoint claims that will be negotiated during the next week.
The mere extent of the meeting -- 13,000 people go into and out at the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists stage nightly shows in which they make fun of the countries that they think are betraying and selling, and contract designs are passed on hand-to-hand rather than by e-mail -- is already a challenge.
