Affaire Liliane Bettencourt: François-Marie Banier is condemned for exploitation of weakness
On Friday, the Court of Nanterre decided to judge the artist François-Marie Banier in order to determine whether, as the daughter of the billionaire Liliane Bettencourt claims, he took advantage of a weak moment of the eighty-year-olds to sneak up part of their fortunes.
The 62-year-old photographer, who is known for his star photos, will have to answer on 15 and 16 April 2010 for exploitation of weakness in court, a criminal offence punishable by a maximum of three years imprisonment and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision means that there will indeed be a process in this affair worthy of the saga of one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter shred themselves and at the same time have the reins of the cosmetic empire L'Oréal in their hands.
However, the 15th Trial Chamber also ordered a medical examination of the 87-year-old Liliane Bettencourt, which is jointly conducted by three doctors.
The heir and principal shareholder of L'Oréal has so far refused to undergo such an investigation, especially under the conditions provided by the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office during the investigation.
The doctors appointed on Friday are expected to present a report before 10 March 2010 in which you will make clear whether and at what times Liliane Bettencourt may have been in a state of weakness.
I think she's gonna go through these tests.
I'll talk to her, the lawyer of Mrs. Bettencourt, Me Georges Kiejman, explained after the trial.
As far as the lawyer of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers, Me Olivier Metzner, is concerned, he is very pleased with the court's decision.
This is an excellent news (...). The report will prove that he (Banier) has manipulated this old lady who must be protected, he affirmed.
For two years, the only daughter of Liliane Bettencourt has initiated a criminal lawsuit against François-Marie Banier, photographer and all-round artist, and accused him of having exploited her mother's weakness for years in order to sneak donations of a total of one billion euros in the form of bank cheques, insurance policies or paintings.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt had always refuted being manipulated by the photographer, whom she sees as a longtime friend.
Although the court had to examine the admissibility of the action brought by Mrs Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers' playdays on Friday led to a large family debacle.
For example, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer called on three letters sent by his client to her notary (1999, 2003 and 2005) in which she wrote that she distrusted Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
According to her lawyer, Liliane Bettencourt added: "Please tell my daughter that I wrote to Banier once or twice a day for fifteen years.
I have never been able to speak to Françoise since her marriage."
The Procuratorate of Nanterre once again considers that the applicant had no right to react in this way, especially because a guardianship judge has refused her request to initiate proceedings against her mother in the last few days.
Liliane Bettencourt "is fully legal, is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one has the right to act in their place," said Marie-Christine Daubigney, representative of the Public Prosecutor's Office.
The Court has now decided to give a judgment after the procedure for the admissibility of Ms Bettencourt-Meyers has taken place.
Manager Revolution or the End of Strategic Early Education?
If nothing changes in the leadership of the big French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence has been in vain ...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies in relation to its employees, said the position of the companies vis-à-vis the consumers before the marketing revolution: It is intended for the personnel to join "values" the best as it used to impose on the consumer products designed by the technicians in the factory.
By placing the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution has given the strategies of conquering the markets in place ... although the authoritarian temptation products separated factors to impose customer preferences again regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to a deadly demoralization.
The suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of a much larger phenomenon that affects employees in particular.
This demobilization has a negative impact on the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially those of R&E and, more importantly, those of economic intelligence.
In fact, the IE (Intelligence Economique = Economic Intelligence) demands "a proactive approach and a forward-looking view from all the parties involved"; it demands from the employees an effort to which the instructions of authoritarian management completely contradict.
That is why we are calling for an operational revolution, which would consist of placing employees in the centre of the company's concerns alongside customers on an equal footing.
The very limited benefits of internal opinion polls
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire that Orange has submitted to its wage recipients, stimulate this revolution in terms of management practice?
I'm afraid not.
First of all, because I could see that, in the face of a new situation, after a lot of detours, the whole structure is finally beginning to do what it has always done.
Also because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of power - increases in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
And finally, because most executives have a much simplified idea of human behavior.
From the major engineering schools, their interpretation of psychology is mechanistic.
Through intellectual comfort, they adopt the old behaviorist theory, which was recently reactivated by the American "neurosciences" and unwittingly widely spread by research institutes and the media.
Thus, and by suggesting that it is possible to use the "hebel" (sic) to engage employees, a recent survey by Ipsos published by Le Figaro.fr strengthens the executives in an attitude towards a mechanistic control system that is unsuitable for today's world.
Identifying and measuring the mobilization factors
Instead, an operational revolution necessary for the smooth functioning of modern enterprises requires the adoption of a definitive view of human behaviour.
It consists of integrating a basic protocol into any consideration or practice of governance: for wage-earners, the commitment to the enterprise is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of achieving a part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
At the moment only the studies from the multifunctional analysis take over this conception of the motivation of the employees.
These studies have shown that they assess their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa, which allows them to estimate what it offers them to achieve their life goals through their perceived image of the company.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, companies' managers can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and place their human resource management back in the right place.
In this way, they create a fertile soil that is favourable for the coordinated development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
The Oslo speech: the "just war" brings Obama praise from the right
American rights welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo on Friday evening and was pleased that the Nobel Peace Prize in 2009 defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who mocked the award to Obama on October 9, applauded the President's speech, following the example of the former Vice-President candidate in the 2008 elections, Sarah Palin.
I liked what he said, Palin explained the face of the Republican Party's right wing in the U.S. Today daily, adding that she herself had raised the issue of a "sometimes necessary" war in her memoirs published as well.
