Drivers: Three marathons for an agreement to secure the supply for Christmas
After a three-week negotiation marathon, the unions of the Road Federation and the TLF - the only employer organization that remained until the end - came to an agreement on Friday evening, which puts an end to the strike order and the imminent severe shortage of supplies for Christmas.
At the signature meeting on Friday evening, Secretary of State Dominique Bussereau, responsible for transport, welcomed the agreement which was launched on Wednesday morning after several weeks of negotiations.
After a second night of negotiations, the negotiators split early on Friday morning hoping to sign the agreement quickly in the late morning.
And this despite the fact that the three employers' associations (FNTR, Unostra and OTRE) had left the meeting.
However, more than six hours passed from the beginning of the meeting at 11:00 a.m. to the conclusion of the agreement, and the agreement was not signed until 6:00 p.m.
The conflict "had caused a great deal of damage to companies" and "it was to be feared that it would affect the holidays at the end of the year," says Bussereau.
The agreement provides for a 4% increase in wages for the lowest wages (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest wage groups (international transports).
The hourly rate for workers with the lowest wages thus rises from 8.72 euros to 9.06 euros.
"That's not very much, but we start small," says Patrice Clos (FO).
Activists are now instructed not to block the supply centres anymore.
"However, there will probably always be some unruly ones who are not satisfied with the agreement," he adds.
TLF Chairman Philippe Grillot spoke of a "good agreement," although it was "difficult to allow these wage increases in the face of international competition."
According to him, the increase is 170 euros per month for the low and 100 to 120 euros for the high wage groups.
"This agreement is based on common sense and respect for employees," says Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) spoke of "a historic agreement."
Richard Jaubert (CGT) spoke about "an acceptable compromise."
The agreement also provides for a 3% increase in travel costs and the maintenance of the overall road transport budget in the first half of 2010, which will enable, in particular, to address the issue of 13th monthly salary and the modernisation of collective agreements.
M. Bussereau recalled that "the fall in employers' taxes of EUR 100 million" was the subject of an amendment by the government to the draft law on adjusted finances for 2009, which was adopted by the National Assembly on the night of Thursday to Friday.
The government demands "an identical" vote from the Senate.
The TLF's signature allows the agreement to apply first to the companies affiliated to the organisation and then applies to the entire profession if the Minister of Labour extends it.
This will be the case "in no time," Bussereau assures.
The opposition of employers' organisations can only delay the proceedings.
The FNTR Association denounced a "false trade" because the EUR 100 million "were already promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax."
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate as soon as possible, but not on the basis of a joint analysis, but in order not to grieve the goose eaters on the approaching Christmas days, the Unostra complains.
For the Otre Association, the agreement threatens "to shovel a large grave for small and medium-sized enterprises in the sector over the next 12 months."
