Turkish Constitutional Court dissolves pro-Kurdish party. Decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court announced on Friday the dissolution of the pro-Kurdish main party of the country; a decision that immediately followed raging demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision threatens to make the work of the government enormously difficult, which is trying to reach out to the Kurdish community in order to put an end to the conflicts which have lasted 25 years.
The "Party for a Democratic Society" (DTP) was dissolved as it had become "a seat for activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," according to the President of the Constitutional Court Hasim Kiliç four days after the decision to the press.
According to Kiliç, the decision would have been taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes required to impose the dissolution. He also pointed out that 37 of the party's leaders, including President Ahmet Türk and parliamentarians Aysel Tugluk, were excluded from political action for a period of five years.
Furthermore, the judge announced the waiver of parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, as well as the confiscation of the party's goods.
The DTP now has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
The party leaders said before the verdict that the parliamentarians would rather leave the parliament than meet like non-partisan parliamentarians.
The decision followed a trial initiated in 2007 by the Prosecutor of the Turkish Federal Court Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya. He accused the DTP of following the "wisdoms" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many other countries consider to be a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political shop window of the PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has "no connection" to the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate.
The verdict of the Constitutional Court sparks the government in between, which strives to meet the Kurdish community and propose a series of measures to strengthen the rights of the Kurds, in order to let the support of the PKK by the Kurds disappear and put an end to the conflicts.
The leaders of the DTP reaffirm that a resolution could lead to a recurrence of tensions in Southeast Anatolia, where numerous demonstrations against the detention conditions of PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan have led to clashes with the police in recent weeks.
Since the court's announcement, thousands of demonstrators have gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, a city of millions, in the southeast, mostly populated by Kurds.
The forces of order used tear gas grenades and water cannons when the demonstrators started throwing Molotov cocktails and stones.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk assumed that the court's decision "will deepen the despair even further."
"Turkey cannot resolve this (Kurdische, anm. d. Redaktion) question on the basis of the prohibition of a party," he explained to the press.
The government, consisting of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also regretted the decision.
"We oppose the closure of the parties on principle.
That does not solve the problems," says Minister of Energy Taner Yildiz.
"This decision is a torpedo of democratic openness promoted by the government," said political market observer Ahmet Island.
"One can obviously prepare for a reaction of the PKK," he adds.
On Thursday, the PKK committed an attack that killed seven soldiers in northern Turkey three days earlier, one of the most brutal attacks in recent months.
The snowfall can come
