Since there is a smoothness on this fast, as soon as the temperature falls below two degrees, the spreader is on the way.
If necessary, he is also called by the police.
The cradle of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-meter-long and 1.50-meter-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it wouldn't be special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body traits, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which then lay in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us much about the relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating on the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
In the course of the excavation, they gathered the remains of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories on Dino early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an extraordinary finding: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only single fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current teaching opinion, the dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these original dinosaurs is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts are debating when the lizards split into their three main lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods known as "Langhälse," and their relatives, and the plant-eating Ornithischia (bird pool saurs), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air bags, as they also possess the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the giant sauropods later also had air bags and lightweight bones, probably the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known so far lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
According to this, the three lines of development separated early on and spread from South America across all parts of the world, which at that time still formed a single land mass as a supercontinent Pangaea.
The fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not very closely related theropods suggests this.
The three cannot descend from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says the Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could be a distorted picture, because in South America many primitive dino fossils have been preserved, while on other continents hardly anything can be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare lateral line of the reptile strain to the dominant terrestrial workings of the Earth's Middle Ages is still mysterious.
During the Triassic, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flying saurs and numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while the kinship on the border from the Triassic to the Jura died out.
Success story didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass death that happened to survive the dinosaurs, but not the other reptiles.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story didn't last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact of a group of animals, which had also developed in the Triassic, helped to bloom, and since then there has been a shadowy existence: the mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and the signatories are international.
Professors at the University of Toronto are on it, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley in California.
Lecturers from Naples are from Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
