New Silicon Valley
For many years it was considered a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenograd, one of ten districts of Moscow's capital, was a strictly guarded location in the Soviet Union for secret military research.
Today, the municipality, with its 216,000 inhabitants, 37 kilometers from Moscow's center, is considered a "Russian Silicon Valley."
Important research and production facilities for micro- and nanoelectronics are located here.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenograd had already made contacts with the Frankfurt science location Riedberg - with the university institutes and the companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Center (FIZ).
There were several mutual visits and on Wednesday Selenograd and Riedberg signed a "protocol for closer cooperation" in Frankfurt.
Moscow Vice-Mayor Yuri Roslyak and Prefect Anatoly Smirnov of Selenograd led the Russian delegation, and Frankfurt signed planning officer Edwin Schwarz.
In 2010, representatives of the FIZ and small and medium-sized companies of the scientific research focus will travel to Selenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
It is about continuous scientific exchange.
But it is also about economic relations.
