Dream worlds
Some see images in a precarious state and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
The boundaries between imagination and reality blur not only in the mentally ill and in the drug rush.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything's fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we are allowed to indulge in the wildest ideas and fantasies.
However, those who experience dreamlike conditions in the growing world, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered crazy or drug addicted in the modern Western world, at least as a special species.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drug rush.
Our imagination is at fault: the same neuronal processes that enable us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes blur the boundaries between dream, delusion and reality.
Dreamlike changing waking consciousness states can occur in a wide variety of forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Although triggers and effects may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic rapture states, psychoses and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of the neuronal messenger substances of the brain - primarily dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction of different brain parts is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over him anymore
The connection between delusion and dream has been occupied by philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dream in the waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, stated in 1861 a "great resemblance of madness with dream states," for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis, with all inconsistencies, delusions, sensuality of such a."
