His diagnosis is schizoaffective-paranoid psychosis, moreover he is manic-depressant, he takes medications, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis, I experienced the worst fear and deepest despair, he says.
The false images are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers can usually no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, they fall into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, grandeur, relationship or persecution delusions.
Voice listening is particularly common - voices that command, comment or diagnose.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The person concerned is no longer able to separate important things from unimportant things, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the locks for a flood of ideas and fantasies that come from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centred, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician of the Clinic for General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the event, everything has a meaning for it.
At the same time he becomes a passive role, he is overwhelmed by the events, similar to the dream, and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A reality balance is usually impossible for them, the illusions are cruel reality, awakening is excluded.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are rooted in reality, the alienation of experience takes place in a real context.
Why exactly our brains are beating caprioles, researchers are still puzzling.
In every human being, states of exception can cause him to lose his reference to reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that the genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, for example, by a mother's viral disease during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains a mystery of how the neuronal system is disturbed, which at first does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can trigger a psychosis when disposition is present.
Also hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis as they intervene in the transmitter system.
When our brains run hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get some, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether false images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a matter of position.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and deceptions for ten years, and last year he evaluated his results in the book "The Irreal World in Our Head."
Halucinations are one of the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's and skull brain trauma.
Surprisingly, even the brain of healthy people is hallucinating under certain conditions.
As Box says, hallucinations are made up of memory contents that are usually held back.
They arise when areas of the brain where sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brain is running hot or also when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can cause this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But also irritating deprivation, stress, heartache or other mental states of exception.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported that they had experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If there weren't the pictures and voices.
During the break, it may happen that a shaky boy with long, dark hair responds to it.
When it answers to him, the classmates look at it surprised - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spooky daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy?, she sometimes asks herself.
But she knows that this boy and the other fakes aren't real and disappear again.
At night, the apparitions are usually scary
Often the false images are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the teaching material, because the teacher is presenting a new classmate in her eyes and ears, while he is explaining mathematical equations for all the others listening and visible on the table.
At night, the apparitions are usually scary.
When she waits for sleep in her dark room, which is far too rare and far too late, she often cannot tell if she is awake or dreaming whether the images she sees, the grunts or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, arise in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, yell at the figures.
Parents and friends don't tell her about it, they think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she contacted the psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows she's not crazy.
Faith is also a work of art out of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from stimuli deprivation, he will most likely have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I guess the brain is then under-employed and is responsible for his own conversation.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she calls Daddy hasn't been her biological father since she could think.
Since the same areas of the brain are active in visual and acoustic hallucinations, which also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for those affected such as Sarah K. to distinguish false images and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is reflected there.
Halucinations are also images that make the brain develop, which is why they seem so real."
Even nightly dream pictures consider Kasten as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
In contrast to schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their illusions as unreal.
Box therefore advises his patients to value the hallucinations as a special ability.
Boundary state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our too consciously centered world, imaginary experience is usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy of the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful illness, but it also contains positive, creative - delusion is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneioid form of experience, a special form of the dreamlike changed wake-consciousness.
Oneiroides are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the survivor considers to be real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state in retrospect.
The oneioid state of consciousness arises in trauma or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by loss of self and world, for example by persistent, total immobility, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of boundary state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to deal with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the real situation is brought to mind in the imagination.
An intense form of meaningfulness and sensuality in an unbearable situation, which enables us humans' own ability to design not to perish in a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a rescue action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation followed by a heart transplant, while his body is sentenced to immobility in the intensive care unit.
Claussen immerses himself in a self-made world, visiting strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages under nobles who produce drugs from blood.
Deported by a Greek on a motorcycle to his home country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the fir snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
He goes completely up in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in memory.
For Claussen, these inner travels are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental travels are still very clear to me after years and in minor details.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience transcends the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oneiroide, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug rush show how fragile our inner images of outer reality are in the guard.
Every change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist summarizes box, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
