75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fruitability and career of women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities on the labour market limited by their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether women work or not, and if so, on the type of occupation they pursue.
Those of them who do no other activity outside the house, only work half-days or have no fixed contract of employment, are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a permanent job, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the 35-49 age group with a permanent job receive their first child on average only 3.7 years after they move together, a figure which increases to 4.1 years for women with a permanent job who have taken longer to achieve this and who have moved together and the first child only achieved it much later.
Moreover, the type of work also has a great influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar with regard to conception readiness," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and in the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference could also be observed among women of the same age.
For example, women in the group aged between 35 and 49 became mothers for the first time, on average 25.1 or 32.1 depending on whether they only have a secondary education or a higher education.
There is also a further difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with a major degree marry before their first permanent job and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree do it exactly the other way around and first find themselves a permanent job and marry afterwards and then have their first child, notes Delgado.
