Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as it is now happening with the ESP stability control system, the emergency braking assistance systems must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, for the remaining vehicles a waiting period was set until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the action decided by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many collisions due to their operation.
The emergency braking assistant's task is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre which the system detects on the brake pedal based on the braking strength carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake support, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system and thus reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car covers during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistance.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents is expected to be prevented by personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
